Geometry & Metrics Engine — Description

The Geometry & Metrics Engine converts raw pose landmarks into structured, quantitative biomechanical data. It is the measurement layer only—no interpretation, no roles—just precise extraction of structural state.

Core Function

Transform 2D pose coordinates into:

joint relationships

alignment deviations

load distribution indicators

movement change across frames

This layer defines what the body is doing, not what it means.

Primary Metric Groups
1. Lower Chain Metrics

foot angle (left/right)

foot angle asymmetry

ankle collapse deviation (corridor-based, not raw angle)

ankle collapse type:

medial (pronation)

lateral (supination)

rotational

knee collapse deviation

knee collapse type:

valgus

varus

rotational

flexion instability

stance width / symmetry

2. Hip & Pelvic Metrics

left/right hip torque (2D proxy)

torque asymmetry

pelvic tilt

pelvic rotation (hip line vs shoulder line)

femur-to-pelvis orientation bias

3. Spine & Upper Chain Metrics

spine lean (global axis)

spine curvature (segment deviation)

spinal segmentation:

cervical

thoracic

lumbar

shoulder tilt

torso shift

4. Center of Mass (COM) Model

global COM deviation

COM drift (frame-to-frame)

dual COM:

upper body COM

lower body COM

COM split offset (upper vs lower disagreement)

5. Structural Corridor Model

Defines acceptable alignment zones per side.

Per side:

corridor center

corridor deviation

breach magnitude (normalized by stance width)

States:

intact

caution

breached

6. Node Burden Model

Each structural node receives a burden score:

Nodes:

foot

ankle

knee

hip

pelvis

trunk

shoulder

cervical/head

Each node tracks:

local burden

transferred burden

compensated burden

persistence across frames

7. Dynamic Metrics

Captured across frames:

ankle collapse change

knee collapse change

COM drift change

pelvic tilt change

corridor change

Used for:

momentum detection

propagation modeling

dynamic state classification

8. Momentum Classification

Based on multi-frame trends:

increasing burden

stable

recovering

oscillating

9. Phase-Aware Adjustment

Dynamic thresholds adapt to movement phase:

left stance

right stance

double support

swing

This prevents false positives during motion.

Normalization & Constraints

all deviations normalized to body scale

corridor normalized by stance width

angles clamped to physiologic ranges

frame gating prevents unstable inputs

Output Characteristics

deterministic (same input → same output)

frame-indexed

unit-consistent (degrees, normalized ratios)

confidence-aware (low-confidence metrics flagged)

Design Boundary (Critical)

This layer does not:

assign TAM roles

determine stability state

identify origin

interpret clinical meaning

It only produces clean, structured biomechanical data for the solver layer.

Purpose in System

The Geometry & Metrics Engine is the foundation of truth.

If this layer is accurate:

solver becomes reliable

origin detection stabilizes

clinical interpretation becomes consistent

If this layer drifts:

everything above it fails

This layer ensures the system always knows:
exactly what the body is doing—frame by frame, side by side, node by node.
